  "prompt": "Why does shaking a soda cause it to explode?",
  "response": "Shaking a soda causes it to explode due to the physics of dissolved carbon dioxide (CO\u2082) gas and the pressure inside the container. Here's a breakdown of the process:\n\n1. **Dissolved CO\u2082**: Sodas are carbonated, meaning they contain dissolved CO\u2082 gas under pressure. When the bottle or can is sealed, the CO\u2082 remains dissolved in the liquid because the high pressure inside the container prevents it from escaping.\n\n2. **Shaking Effect**: When you shake the soda, you introduce energy into the system. This energy causes the dissolved CO\u2082 to come out of solution and form tiny bubbles throughout the liquid. These bubbles create additional surface area for more CO\u2082 to escape from the liquid.\n\n3. **Pressure Buildup**: As more CO\u2082 gas is released into the bubbles, the pressure inside the container increases. The gas takes up more space than the liquid, and the sealed container cannot expand to accommodate the increased pressure.\n\n4. **Opening the Container**: When you open the soda, the sudden drop in external pressure allows the gas to expand rapidly. The CO\u2082 bubbles in the liquid grow quickly, pushing the liquid out of the container in a foam or spray, causing the \"explosion.\"\n\n5. **Foam Formation**: The rapid release of CO\u2082 also creates foam, as the gas bubbles trap the liquid. This foam can overflow or spray out violently, depending on how much pressure has built up.\n\nTo minimize the risk of exploding soda, avoid shaking it and open it slowly to allow the pressure to release gradually. Chilling the soda beforehand also helps, as CO\u2082 stays dissolved more effectively at lower temperatures.",
